{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501180"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:25:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:25:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1728"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1728"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.01,0.02,0.18,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103438"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1728"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85860"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36724"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103438"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman presents with a 24-hour history of vomiting, abdominal pain, and distension. She underwent an appendicectomy 15 years earlier and is otherwise in good health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 132/86 mmHg, pulse 108/min and temperature 37.2C. Her abdomen is soft and distended, with tinkling bowel sounds. There is an irreducible tender mass in the right groin, immediately below the inguinal ligament. This does not have a cough impulse. An abdominal X-ray is performed. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal CT with oral and intravenous contrast","Gram stain on a fine needle aspirate of the lump","Incision and drainage of the groin lump","Ultrasound examination of the lump","Surgical exploration of the groin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has the clinical features of bowel obstruction (vomiting, abdominal pain and distension) and a tender lump in the groin lump. The groin lump is almost certainly an obstructed hernia, with impending strangulation. Tenderness of a hernia implies strangulation. The term \u0027strangulation\u0027 implies an ischaemic element, with the risk of infarction, necrosis and perforation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth obstructed and strangulated hernias tend to present with signs of bowel obstruction. A strangulated hernia may present with localised symptoms and signs (Richter hernia). In advanced cases, strangulated hernias can be associated with a toxic appearance and systemic symptoms (eg, fever). While most femoral hernias may have a positive cough impulse, this is usually only seen in reducible or irreducible femoral hernias. Obstructed and strangulated hernias do not generally show a positive cough impulse. Based on the clinical suspicion of obstructed femoral hernia, this patient needs to undergo urgent \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical exploration of the groin\u003C/strong\u003E with herniorrhaphy, no matter what the X-ray shows. Delaying the definitive surgical repair increases the risk of strangulation and necrosis of herniated bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn abdominal CT with oral contrast and groin ultrasound may be used to diagnose a femoral hernia in patients where clinical diagnosis is uncertain. This patient has high clinical suspicion of a strangulated femoral hernia and definitive treatment should not be delayed for diagnostic confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGram stain and incision and draining may be appropriate if the patient had a groin abscess. However, an abscess presents with a septic presentation. Signs of bowel obstruction are unlikely to be associated with an abscess.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A tender swelling in the groin of a patient with signs of intestinal obstruction supports the diagnosis of a strangulated hernia."],"references":["Goethals A, Azmat CE, Adams CT. Femoral Hernia. [Updated 2020 Nov 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535449/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85860"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1728"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15330"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15330"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f4a018f7-88d8-44ad-a759-a35f2d086e24.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f4a018f7-88d8-44ad-a759-a35f2d086e24.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":330,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85860"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-22T14:11:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T14:11:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1728"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103438"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"re